00:59:26.227 --> 00:59:28.060
There's a big question
of what's a security?

00:59:28.060 --> 00:59:28.870
What's a commodity?

00:59:28.870 --> 00:59:30.730
What's a derivative?

00:59:30.730 --> 00:59:34.630
And in every legal
jurisdiction around the globe,

00:59:34.630 --> 00:59:37.600
securities exchanges are
regulated pretty much

00:59:37.600 --> 00:59:40.050
in every jurisdiction.

00:59:40.050 --> 00:59:42.590
So what is a security
and what's not a security

00:59:42.590 --> 00:59:47.120
does relate to what's currently
regulated under current law.

00:59:47.120 --> 00:59:48.830
I've testified in
the US Congress.

00:59:48.830 --> 00:59:52.970
And I'd say regardless of that,
if it's even just a commodity,

00:59:52.970 --> 00:59:56.360
like Bitcoin under US law
is considered a commodity,

00:59:56.360 --> 00:59:59.180
you probably want these
exchanges regulated.

00:59:59.180 --> 01:00:02.060
And if it's a derivative,
in most jurisdictions,

01:00:02.060 --> 01:00:03.990
it also is regulated.

01:00:03.990 --> 01:00:06.020
So the first and the
third in that list,

01:00:06.020 --> 01:00:09.620
securities and derivatives,
exchanges are regulated.

01:00:09.620 --> 01:00:15.080
In most jurisdictions, commodity
exchanges are not, but not all.

01:00:15.080 --> 01:00:20.670
So the definitional thing
also relates to what comes in.

01:00:20.670 --> 01:00:23.630
So in the US, there are
a number of exchanges

