01:01:24.270 --> 01:01:26.873
Tracking beneficial ownership.

01:01:26.873 --> 01:01:29.040
We've tracked beneficial
ownership in the securities

01:01:29.040 --> 01:01:33.450
markets for a long time,
from the first joint stock

01:01:33.450 --> 01:01:34.680
companies.

01:01:34.680 --> 01:01:37.110
Because you track
beneficial ownership

01:01:37.110 --> 01:01:39.550
to ensure that somebody
gets their dividends.

01:01:39.550 --> 01:01:42.420
And if they're voting once a
year on the board of directors

01:01:42.420 --> 01:01:43.770
and things like that.

01:01:43.770 --> 01:01:46.620
But somewhere in the
last 30 or 40 years,

01:01:46.620 --> 01:01:49.230
law enforcement agencies
said that's a good way

01:01:49.230 --> 01:01:51.810
to track against money
laundering and track

01:01:51.810 --> 01:01:53.700
against other things.

01:01:53.700 --> 01:01:57.694
So layered on top
of securities laws,

01:01:57.694 --> 01:01:59.740
law enforcement agencies
around the globe

01:01:59.740 --> 01:02:03.330
said, we want to
know who owns what.

01:02:03.330 --> 01:02:06.060
For the prior 50
to 100 years, it

01:02:06.060 --> 01:02:08.520
was just securities law
that cared about tracking

01:02:08.520 --> 01:02:10.615
beneficial ownership.

01:02:10.615 --> 01:02:12.240
But there's some
international treaty--

01:02:12.240 --> 01:02:13.615
I can't remember
the name of it--

01:02:13.615 --> 01:02:15.540
that says all securities
regulators have

01:02:15.540 --> 01:02:18.120
to do something
extra and make sure

01:02:18.120 --> 01:02:20.100
that there's transfer agents.

01:02:20.100 --> 01:02:22.440
And there's this whole
regime of keeping

01:02:22.440 --> 01:02:26.010
ledgers of who owns what.

01:02:26.010 --> 01:02:28.470
In addition to this
anti-money laundering stuff,

01:02:28.470 --> 01:02:34.070
securities laws have this
embedded in most jurisdictions,

01:02:34.070 --> 01:02:35.980
This is a tough
one for this space,

01:02:35.980 --> 01:02:41.440
not only because it comes
from a libertarian basis.

01:02:41.440 --> 01:02:44.500
But it's also a tough
one just technologically,

01:02:44.500 --> 01:02:46.690
just the technical solutions.

01:02:46.690 --> 01:02:49.330
The crypto exchanges,
half of them

01:02:49.330 --> 01:02:53.980
have what Crypto Compare says
is strict anti-money laundering.

01:02:53.980 --> 01:02:57.370
But 1/4 don't have any,
which means they're not

01:02:57.370 --> 01:03:00.590
tracking beneficial ownership.

01:03:00.590 --> 01:03:05.120
I think that will
slowly get ramped up.

01:03:05.120 --> 01:03:10.940
But if you see a lot of
registered exchanges leaving

01:03:10.940 --> 01:03:13.310
one country for another,
they're probably

01:03:13.310 --> 01:03:16.440
going to a place that
has lower regulation.

