01:08:19.890 --> 01:08:22.840
And they report a lot of volume.

01:08:22.840 --> 01:08:25.325
So it's just an interesting
statistic to sort of say--

01:08:27.930 --> 01:08:30.930
and it might well be that
Binance's volume statistics

01:08:30.930 --> 01:08:32.420
are accurate.

01:08:32.420 --> 01:08:35.340
They're just a crypto
to crypto exchange.

01:08:35.340 --> 01:08:37.996
But they also, their ratio
of visitors to volume

01:08:37.996 --> 01:08:39.329
is very different than Coinbase.

01:08:42.439 --> 01:08:46.370
Just to give you a little flavor
for the craziness out there.

01:08:46.370 --> 01:08:47.359
Investor protection.

01:08:47.359 --> 01:08:50.399
I sort of said investor
protection is critical.

01:08:50.399 --> 01:08:52.910
We're going to talk about
this in a week or so

01:08:52.910 --> 01:08:54.420
about initial coin offerings.

01:08:54.420 --> 01:08:57.710
But it's further than
consumer protection.

01:08:57.710 --> 01:09:00.560
And importantly,
because we address.

01:09:00.560 --> 01:09:01.130
We know.

01:09:01.130 --> 01:09:01.742
We are honest.

01:09:01.742 --> 01:09:02.700
We're earnest about it.

01:09:02.700 --> 01:09:04.575
We say, yes, there are
conflicts of interest.

01:09:04.575 --> 01:09:06.290
How can we address
conflicts of interest?

01:09:06.290 --> 01:09:08.160
You don't ban
conflicts of interest.

01:09:08.160 --> 01:09:11.180
But you sort of say, is
there ways to manage it?

01:09:11.180 --> 01:09:13.189
How do we promote
market integrity

01:09:13.189 --> 01:09:16.970
through transparency and
rules of anti-manipulation?

01:09:16.970 --> 01:09:20.740
So it's kind of those, you
know, the realities of humanity.

01:09:20.740 --> 01:09:23.930
And we say, well, how can we
sort of put some traffic lights

01:09:23.930 --> 01:09:29.460
and speed limits in the system
to give people confidence

01:09:29.460 --> 01:09:30.720
that drive the roads?

01:09:30.720 --> 01:09:33.155
And by the way, Rahim,
I can't tell you,

01:09:33.155 --> 01:09:35.530
because I wasn't there around
the debates in the nineteen

01:09:35.530 --> 01:09:37.145
teens and the 1920s.

01:09:37.145 --> 01:09:38.520
But you can be
assured there were

01:09:38.520 --> 01:09:44.990
debates in whether to put
the first traffic light out.

01:09:44.990 --> 01:09:46.700
Literally, you know?

01:09:46.700 --> 01:09:49.040
Whether to put the
first crosswalks.

01:09:49.040 --> 01:09:51.350
And do traffic
lights and crosswalks

01:09:51.350 --> 01:09:54.260
restrict the use of automobiles?

01:09:54.260 --> 01:09:56.590
Absolutely.

01:09:56.590 --> 01:09:58.240
Absolutely.

01:09:58.240 --> 01:09:59.990
But think about this.

01:09:59.990 --> 01:10:03.430
Did they promote the
sales of automobiles?

01:10:03.430 --> 01:10:05.290
And I would contend
they also promoted

01:10:05.290 --> 01:10:07.300
the sales of automobiles.

01:10:07.300 --> 01:10:10.780
That simple regulatory
intervention

01:10:10.780 --> 01:10:14.020
meant that people could
feel a little bit more safe

01:10:14.020 --> 01:10:15.490
having their neighbors drive.

01:10:15.490 --> 01:10:17.350
Because most people
didn't drive.

01:10:17.350 --> 01:10:19.530
But having their
neighbors come down

01:10:19.530 --> 01:10:23.560
pass there walking on the
street, the pedestrians.

01:10:23.560 --> 01:10:25.610
Pedestrians felt safer.

01:10:25.610 --> 01:10:28.650
So I think it's a bit of both.

01:10:28.650 --> 01:10:32.310
All right, I might be
disclosing my point of view.

01:10:32.310 --> 01:10:35.460
I think investor protection
bolsters investor confidence

01:10:35.460 --> 01:10:36.600
in capital markets.

01:10:36.600 --> 01:10:37.890
And that everybody benefits.

01:10:37.890 --> 01:10:40.590
But you've got to get
the balance right.

01:10:40.590 --> 01:10:42.510
And I'd respect if
half of you say,

01:10:42.510 --> 01:10:45.180
no, it should be less
regulation, and have said more.

01:10:45.180 --> 01:10:47.580
I'm disclosing more
where I am and at least

01:10:47.580 --> 01:10:51.240
the logic behind it.

01:10:51.240 --> 01:10:53.195
You know what the Howey Test is.

01:10:53.195 --> 01:10:54.570
We'll come back
to this in a week

01:10:54.570 --> 01:10:57.780
when we do initial
coin offerings.

01:10:57.780 --> 01:10:59.700
In the center of
crypto exchanges,

01:10:59.700 --> 01:11:03.330
it's an important issue as to
which crypto exchanges have

01:11:03.330 --> 01:11:05.190
an ICO token.

01:11:05.190 --> 01:11:09.990
Then they've got to kind
of do a little bit more.

01:11:09.990 --> 01:11:11.640
Hacks.

01:11:11.640 --> 01:11:13.920
These are the biggest
hacks I could find.

01:11:13.920 --> 01:11:15.180
These are reported hacks.

01:11:15.180 --> 01:11:17.370
Who knows what's
not been reported?

01:11:17.370 --> 01:11:21.750
Coincheck and Mount Gox
each about a half a billion.

01:11:21.750 --> 01:11:26.750
A couple of 50 to 100, 200.

01:11:26.750 --> 01:11:30.130
And here's a bunch of
tiny ones that I've put.

01:11:30.130 --> 01:11:31.480
I mean, they'll be on Canvas.

01:11:31.480 --> 01:11:34.240
But there's a
bunch of basically,

01:11:34.240 --> 01:11:38.590
steal somebody else's coins,
because they're [INAUDIBLE]..

01:11:38.590 --> 01:11:42.230
Earlier question, cold storage.

01:11:42.230 --> 01:11:46.510
This again, thanks to the
friends at Crypto Compare.

01:11:46.510 --> 01:11:49.130
Isabella, that was your
question earlier, right?

01:11:49.130 --> 01:11:52.430
So I can't really tell
you why BitFlyer only

01:11:52.430 --> 01:11:56.760
has 80% in cold storage.

01:11:56.760 --> 01:12:01.080
And some of these others,
like Bit for Nexus 96% or 97%.

01:12:01.080 --> 01:12:04.450
But I think that if you have
a high volume and high flow,

01:12:04.450 --> 01:12:07.980
you could maybe keep
more in cold storage.

01:12:07.980 --> 01:12:11.340
Or if your model is more about
custody than transactions,

01:12:11.340 --> 01:12:12.960
you could have more
in cold storage.

01:12:12.960 --> 01:12:17.370
You do need something, you
know, probably connected

01:12:17.370 --> 01:12:21.390
to give your customer
base liquidity.

01:12:21.390 --> 01:12:23.520
And somewhat depends
how long it takes

01:12:23.520 --> 01:12:27.740
you to move something from
cold storage to hot storage.

01:12:27.740 --> 01:12:29.372
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:12:29.372 --> 01:12:30.330
PROFESSOR: What's that?

01:12:30.330 --> 01:12:33.450
AUDIENCE: At least they used
their own capital [INAUDIBLE]??

01:12:33.450 --> 01:12:35.020
PROFESSOR: So they self-insure.

01:12:35.020 --> 01:12:36.640
And Gemini announced
that they just

01:12:36.640 --> 01:12:39.760
signed a contract with Aion
one of the world's largest

01:12:39.760 --> 01:12:44.830
insurance companies, to
insure against loss of that

01:12:44.830 --> 01:12:46.990
which they're having custody.

01:12:46.990 --> 01:12:49.390
But don't confuse it
for 100% insurance.

01:12:49.390 --> 01:12:52.930
The insurance companies
are charging significantly,

01:12:52.930 --> 01:12:56.260
somewhere around 1.5% a quarter.

01:12:56.260 --> 01:12:58.250
So there's some
crypto exchanges,

01:12:58.250 --> 01:13:01.320
which will allow you to
pay for the insurance.

01:13:04.770 --> 01:13:07.340
And Gemini says they've
signed a contract with Aion.

01:13:07.340 --> 01:13:09.840
And I can't quite tell whether
that's just because Gemini is

01:13:09.840 --> 01:13:11.550
going to pay for the insurance.

01:13:11.550 --> 01:13:13.710
Or they're going
to allow you to pay

01:13:13.710 --> 01:13:19.167
for the insurance in
that custody solution.

01:13:19.167 --> 01:13:20.000
Let's see what else.

01:13:20.000 --> 01:13:22.080
Oh, we're almost wrapping.

01:13:22.080 --> 01:13:23.400
So here's what I think.

01:13:23.400 --> 01:13:26.040
Custody, I think
the custody duties

01:13:26.040 --> 01:13:28.500
either have to be
fixed or spun off.

01:13:28.500 --> 01:13:30.510
I think from a public
policy perspective,

01:13:30.510 --> 01:13:32.310
they're better spun off.

01:13:32.310 --> 01:13:35.640
And that's because there's
such an inherent conflict.

01:13:35.640 --> 01:13:37.590
I think if you're
holding somebody's funds

01:13:37.590 --> 01:13:41.790
and also transacting, it's just
too sweet a honeypot not just

01:13:41.790 --> 01:13:44.940
to be stolen, but for
the operator to say,

01:13:44.940 --> 01:13:48.390
I want to use it in my own--

01:13:48.390 --> 01:13:52.140
lend it, borrow it,
transact around it.

01:13:52.140 --> 01:13:53.880
But that's my thought.

01:13:53.880 --> 01:13:59.100
Fix it or spin it off
would be the custody.

01:13:59.100 --> 01:14:02.910
Illicit activity, I think we're
going to have to get to a place

01:14:02.910 --> 01:14:07.950
where if not 100%, close to
100% are actually complying.

01:14:07.950 --> 01:14:11.610
And if 1/4 of them aren't
even doing AML and KYC,

01:14:11.610 --> 01:14:14.820
there's still a lot of--
there's some road ahead here.

01:14:14.820 --> 01:14:20.310
I know it might not fit, Rahim,
with the libertarian soul

01:14:20.310 --> 01:14:22.560
of the genesis of all this.

01:14:22.560 --> 01:14:24.750
I won't say you
maybe personally.

01:14:28.410 --> 01:14:30.900
I think that's going to
be the path for our--

01:14:30.900 --> 01:14:32.490
if we're still two
and three years

01:14:32.490 --> 01:14:35.730
from now 1/4 of the
market not doing it.

01:14:35.730 --> 01:14:37.470
I think that the
market integrity

01:14:37.470 --> 01:14:38.820
piece is the toughest one.

01:14:38.820 --> 01:14:41.160
And it's maybe where
my own personal views

01:14:41.160 --> 01:14:42.480
shouldn't cloud my judgment.

01:14:42.480 --> 01:14:45.360
My own personal views is
we need market integrity,

01:14:45.360 --> 01:14:49.290
anti-manipulation, no front
running, things like that.

01:14:49.290 --> 01:14:50.930
But realistically,
it's probably going

01:14:50.930 --> 01:14:52.890
to be done by
individual exchanges

01:14:52.890 --> 01:14:55.470
or self-regulatory
organizations.

01:14:55.470 --> 01:14:57.240
Gemini and others
in the UK, there's

01:14:57.240 --> 01:14:59.610
some self-regulatory
organizations.

01:14:59.610 --> 01:15:02.260
I don't think that's sufficient.

01:15:02.260 --> 01:15:04.298
It's a step really in
the right direction.

01:15:04.298 --> 01:15:06.090
But I think somewhere,
if this gets bigger,

01:15:06.090 --> 01:15:09.690
it needs to be the official
sector putting some traffic

01:15:09.690 --> 01:15:14.490
lights and stop signs in.

01:15:14.490 --> 01:15:16.740
Registration and remediation.

01:15:16.740 --> 01:15:18.840
First, to determine whether
you have to register

01:15:18.840 --> 01:15:20.220
and then comply.

01:15:20.220 --> 01:15:23.460
And that's a multiple
month or year period.

01:15:23.460 --> 01:15:26.670
In Japan, they started
registering in late 2017.

01:15:26.670 --> 01:15:28.890
They started with
16 and another 16.

01:15:28.890 --> 01:15:31.610
Some had to shut down in Japan.

01:15:31.610 --> 01:15:33.710
South Korea is registering.

01:15:33.710 --> 01:15:35.550
Now, some of those
registration regimes

01:15:35.550 --> 01:15:39.530
are really just about
custody and Bank Secrecy Act.

01:15:39.530 --> 01:15:42.020
They're not going as far
as I would like to go,

01:15:42.020 --> 01:15:44.240
which is into market integrity.

01:15:44.240 --> 01:15:46.760
But I think you're going to
see a bunch more jurisdictions,

01:15:46.760 --> 01:15:51.860
registration, remediation,
some closing, and the like.

01:15:51.860 --> 01:15:55.640
Margin and fee compression,
I think that's inevitable,

01:15:55.640 --> 01:15:59.400
whether it comes from the Robin
Hoods or the Intercontinental

01:15:59.400 --> 01:16:00.650
Exchange.

01:16:00.650 --> 01:16:03.540
But the juice is
so much right now.

01:16:03.540 --> 01:16:06.620
I mean, some of these
are charging 1% to 3%.

01:16:06.620 --> 01:16:07.730
You all transact.

01:16:07.730 --> 01:16:09.260
You know your fee
structures better.

01:16:09.260 --> 01:16:12.910
But I think there'll be
margin and fee compression.

01:16:12.910 --> 01:16:14.810
And I think there'll
be some consolidation.

01:16:14.810 --> 01:16:19.580
There's not enough room
here for 200 plus exchanges.

01:16:19.580 --> 01:16:21.860
So those are my predictions.

01:16:21.860 --> 01:16:24.470
And I think the
decentralized exchanges,

01:16:24.470 --> 01:16:26.910
once they have
enhanced customer UI,

01:16:26.910 --> 01:16:28.220
there will be more adoption.

01:16:28.220 --> 01:16:33.890
But right now, not that easy
to use for most regular people,

01:16:33.890 --> 01:16:36.605
the non-computer scientists.

